1
00:00:00,500 --> 00:00:04,670
Speaker 16: Hi, my name is Pavel Shokhov,
and today we'll talk about building

2
00:00:04,690 --> 00:00:09,310
LLM voice agents for people who don't
trust AI or for those who do trust AI.

3
00:00:09,810 --> 00:00:13,420
First of all, I'm a founding
engineer at Sofi Connect and a

4
00:00:13,420 --> 00:00:14,769
co-founder at DENG Solutions.

5
00:00:15,199 --> 00:00:19,330
Today, we'll mostly talk about
my experience at Sofi Connect and

6
00:00:19,330 --> 00:00:21,369
the stuff that we built there.

7
00:00:21,869 --> 00:00:30,569
So What we wanted to do is to give a,
our users a curated experience, not

8
00:00:30,609 --> 00:00:34,669
just an app with a menu, something
that feels exclusive, personal,

9
00:00:34,739 --> 00:00:36,529
and closer to a concierge service.

10
00:00:37,519 --> 00:00:42,479
And for this, we chose voice
AI as our main feature that we

11
00:00:42,479 --> 00:00:44,249
were building in the dating.

12
00:00:44,749 --> 00:00:48,729
The assumption was that this kind of
interaction could increase retention and

13
00:00:48,759 --> 00:00:50,869
make users more involved in the product.

14
00:00:51,499 --> 00:00:54,930
At the beginning, we had two
options we wanted to test.

15
00:00:55,279 --> 00:00:58,749
It's voice AI inside the app,
the more conventional and common

16
00:00:58,750 --> 00:01:00,879
approach, and voice AI over the phone

17
00:01:01,379 --> 00:01:01,999
Why phone?

18
00:01:02,849 --> 00:01:06,819
The reason we chose phone calls was
based on our target demographic,

19
00:01:07,229 --> 00:01:12,169
which was like 55 plus, 60 plus
years old people in the beginning.

20
00:01:12,579 --> 00:01:16,179
And our assumption was that our
users were already used to the phone

21
00:01:16,209 --> 00:01:19,859
as a calling tool, and it would be
easier to onboard them this way.

22
00:01:20,399 --> 00:01:23,669
They would not need to learn app
mechanics, download anything,

23
00:01:23,669 --> 00:01:27,199
create an account, or go
through registration, et cetera.

24
00:01:27,479 --> 00:01:31,079
They would simply call the number and
they would already be inside the service.

25
00:01:31,749 --> 00:01:36,729
After that, we could call c- call
them back or text them when we needed.

26
00:01:37,239 --> 00:01:40,659
The idea sounded great in theory,
but in practice we faced several

27
00:01:40,659 --> 00:01:45,839
problems So first group of problems
was connected to perception and trust.

28
00:01:46,239 --> 00:01:48,609
Many people do not want to talk to robots.

29
00:01:48,609 --> 00:01:50,659
Many people also do not like the word AI.

30
00:01:50,899 --> 00:01:53,319
For some users, just
knowing that something is AI

31
00:01:53,659 --> 00:01:55,059
already creates resistance.

32
00:01:55,929 --> 00:01:59,240
There were also issues with
accents where speech-to-text could

33
00:01:59,240 --> 00:02:01,009
fail or misunderstand the user.

34
00:02:01,539 --> 00:02:03,449
Another major issue was scam fear.

35
00:02:03,819 --> 00:02:07,029
When someone receives a call from
an unknown number, especially if the

36
00:02:07,029 --> 00:02:11,390
service is new, it can feel easily,
it can easily feel suspicious.

37
00:02:11,890 --> 00:02:16,670
The next group of problems was
connected to unexpected human behavior.

38
00:02:17,340 --> 00:02:21,620
Some users also did not fully
understand what they were talking

39
00:02:21,640 --> 00:02:23,220
to, who they were talking to.

40
00:02:23,720 --> 00:02:27,510
They were talking to AI, and because
of that, they went off script, asking

41
00:02:27,510 --> 00:02:31,980
related questions, shared personal
stories, even some of them started

42
00:02:31,980 --> 00:02:37,399
flirting with the AI and all of these
unexpected interactions cost us money

43
00:02:37,880 --> 00:02:43,109
as we need to continue talking with the
users, but get them back on, on the track.

44
00:02:43,399 --> 00:02:46,740
So we had to introduce some
guardrails for that A very

45
00:02:46,740 --> 00:02:48,890
important thing is designing trust.

46
00:02:49,390 --> 00:02:51,320
The first was the voice.

47
00:02:51,440 --> 00:02:54,740
The voice should be calm,
pleasant, and trustworthy.

48
00:02:55,050 --> 00:02:59,920
We chose a neutral female voice from
the latest ElevenLab models at the

49
00:02:59,920 --> 00:03:02,570
time because they sounded less robotic.

50
00:03:03,280 --> 00:03:06,540
The second thing was giving
the bot a neutral name.

51
00:03:06,540 --> 00:03:09,700
It humanizes the experience,
and we named our bot Sophie.

52
00:03:10,340 --> 00:03:15,110
At the same time, it is important to
say at the beginning that this was AI.

53
00:03:15,900 --> 00:03:23,910
Also it is regulated by certain local
laws in the US, so you had… you have

54
00:03:23,910 --> 00:03:28,280
to tell the user that they are not
talking to to a person at the beginning.

55
00:03:29,070 --> 00:03:32,330
And we worked carefully on the
phrase because the goal was to be

56
00:03:32,330 --> 00:03:34,780
transparent without scaring people away.

57
00:03:35,560 --> 00:03:39,400
We also decided not to have any
visual reference of Sophie anywhere.

58
00:03:40,230 --> 00:03:43,760
If you decide what the assistant should
look like, you may build trust with some

59
00:03:43,770 --> 00:03:50,090
users, but lose others because of their
expectations or their beauty standards.

60
00:03:50,600 --> 00:03:54,440
Think about Siri, Alexa, or
other popular voice assistants.

61
00:03:54,750 --> 00:03:58,690
There is a reason they usually do not
have a human-like visual representation.

62
00:03:59,630 --> 00:04:03,280
Another trust-related detail
is caller identification.

63
00:04:03,740 --> 00:04:07,420
We ask users to add our number
to their contacts so they see who

64
00:04:07,420 --> 00:04:09,580
is calling them or texting them.

65
00:04:09,920 --> 00:04:14,320
We also added calling name presentation
so that when we called users, they

66
00:04:14,320 --> 00:04:19,520
could see who was calling even if
they didn't have us in their contacts.

67
00:04:20,020 --> 00:04:22,330
Finally, memory is extremely important.

68
00:04:22,360 --> 00:04:27,110
We used Memzero for that, and if you
build memory, the bot can talk to the

69
00:04:27,120 --> 00:04:29,040
user based on previous conversations.

70
00:04:29,450 --> 00:04:33,580
That makes a real difference between a
simple script and personalized experience.

71
00:04:33,950 --> 00:04:39,240
For example, when the user can pull up
some some d- some small details from

72
00:04:39,240 --> 00:04:46,500
the old conversations, so the user
feels that the bot remembers some small

73
00:04:46,540 --> 00:04:52,990
personal think about things about them,
and it feels it feels great for anyone

74
00:04:53,490 --> 00:04:57,370
The next thing we had
to work on was scripts.

75
00:04:57,550 --> 00:05:01,760
Every word said to the user should be
thought through and every phase every

76
00:05:01,780 --> 00:05:03,400
phrase should be replayed out loud.

77
00:05:03,830 --> 00:05:07,500
When you look at the phrase in the text,
it may seem short, but when the bot says

78
00:05:07,500 --> 00:05:09,680
it out loud, it can feel much longer.

79
00:05:10,640 --> 00:05:14,230
To reduce off-script dialogues,
you also need a guardrail system.

80
00:05:14,650 --> 00:05:17,620
It should detect when the user
starts talking about something

81
00:05:17,620 --> 00:05:21,310
unrelated and politely bring them
back to the dialogue scenario.

82
00:05:21,800 --> 00:05:26,990
As I said earlier, every off-script
dialogue costs you money, but

83
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:30,370
you cannot interrupt the person.

84
00:05:30,540 --> 00:05:32,520
You should politely bring them back

85
00:05:33,020 --> 00:05:36,480
Another thing we had to work
on is phone infrastructure.

86
00:05:36,830 --> 00:05:41,740
It's like a second group of problems,
technical problems, while previous ones

87
00:05:41,740 --> 00:05:43,200
were more connected to the product.

88
00:05:43,820 --> 00:05:47,860
These are connected to the tech
issues with using phone calls and

89
00:05:47,870 --> 00:05:50,840
text messages as the primary way
to communicate with the users.

90
00:05:51,160 --> 00:05:55,960
For example, machine answers and voicemail
detection, calls being blocked by

91
00:05:55,960 --> 00:06:00,770
providers, people calling from landline
phones where you cannot send them a text

92
00:06:00,770 --> 00:06:07,100
message back, SMS delivery not being 100%,
not having an app, which means you lose

93
00:06:07,100 --> 00:06:11,180
some control over the user journey, and
of course, the costs that are connected

94
00:06:11,220 --> 00:06:13,790
to using such way of communication.

95
00:06:14,620 --> 00:06:18,110
There are many technical issues
you can face, and first and most

96
00:06:18,110 --> 00:06:20,480
obvious o-of them is latency.

97
00:06:20,820 --> 00:06:25,510
It's a technical challenge, but at
least it has relatively clear solutions.

98
00:06:25,700 --> 00:06:30,800
You can optimize networking, optimize
your code, your database, move your

99
00:06:30,800 --> 00:06:35,390
infrastructure closer to users, use
faster AI providers, and if you can

100
00:06:35,440 --> 00:06:39,790
run speech-to-text models locally,
you should absolutely consider it.

101
00:06:40,550 --> 00:06:45,660
A good benchmark is having end-to-end
latency around 500 to 700 milliseconds.

102
00:06:46,150 --> 00:06:49,180
That is usually sufficient,
and it feels like talking to

103
00:06:49,180 --> 00:06:50,470
a real human over the phone.

104
00:06:50,970 --> 00:06:56,500
This includes VAD detection, then the
LLM starting to stream the answer and the

105
00:06:56,500 --> 00:06:59,540
first text-to-speech audio chunk arriving.

106
00:07:00,050 --> 00:07:04,810
It's all of top all, all on the
top of phone network latency.

107
00:07:05,420 --> 00:07:08,220
But some phone specific
problems are harder to solve.

108
00:07:08,550 --> 00:07:13,330
For example, calls can be blocked by
local providers or you can get sudden

109
00:07:13,340 --> 00:07:17,810
drop-offs and in some cases, there
is not much you can do about it.

110
00:07:18,440 --> 00:07:21,960
One of the most interesting problems
Was machine answer detection.

111
00:07:22,460 --> 00:07:25,290
It's like one of the most
unexpected problems, I would say.

112
00:07:25,730 --> 00:07:28,880
At first, it feels like a problem
that should be easy to solve, but

113
00:07:28,880 --> 00:07:30,810
in practice, you still get mistakes.

114
00:07:31,200 --> 00:07:34,450
When you call a person in the
US, you may reach voicemail.

115
00:07:34,670 --> 00:07:38,600
In our service, it was crucial to
detect voicemail correctly because

116
00:07:38,630 --> 00:07:42,130
undetected voicemail could heavily
influence other people's experience.

117
00:07:42,700 --> 00:07:46,010
In the simplest case, undetected
voicemail is just a loss of money,

118
00:07:46,480 --> 00:07:52,350
but in other cases, it can be a
ruined user journey and just a overall

119
00:07:52,360 --> 00:07:54,560
bad experience and a lost customer.

120
00:07:55,330 --> 00:08:00,330
The easiest solution is to activate
AMD, it's automated machine detection.

121
00:08:00,600 --> 00:08:03,650
It is included in most
telephony providers.

122
00:08:04,030 --> 00:08:08,350
We used Twilio's AMD as Twilio
was our telephony provider.

123
00:08:08,940 --> 00:08:11,170
However, it was not perfect, of course.

124
00:08:11,500 --> 00:08:13,860
So the next layer that
we added was heuristics.

125
00:08:13,900 --> 00:08:18,750
For example, we looked for short phrases
or markers of a machine answer, such

126
00:08:18,750 --> 00:08:24,250
as many numbers being said one after
another, like you're re- you're trying

127
00:08:24,250 --> 00:08:26,520
to reach one, two, three, four, five.

128
00:08:27,350 --> 00:08:30,990
Like when the voicemail system
reads out the phone you have called.

129
00:08:31,900 --> 00:08:35,950
We also looked for phrases like, "You have
called," "You have reached," "Can answer,"

130
00:08:36,150 --> 00:08:38,010
and similar voicemail style phrases.

131
00:08:38,690 --> 00:08:41,510
Then the next layer was
running LLM-based detection.

132
00:08:42,330 --> 00:08:48,030
It was possible only after some period
of time when we have collected a lot

133
00:08:48,030 --> 00:08:53,530
of different examples of the machine
answers, yeah, specific to our users,

134
00:08:53,540 --> 00:09:00,140
so we could build an LLM-based detection
system We also worked a lot on our text

135
00:09:00,140 --> 00:09:02,980
agent and it had its own specifics.

136
00:09:03,100 --> 00:09:07,140
So we had text agent that what,
that, that was talking to the

137
00:09:07,150 --> 00:09:09,360
users over the text messages.

138
00:09:10,100 --> 00:09:14,140
First, every message costs you
money and SMS is charged not

139
00:09:14,140 --> 00:09:15,620
per message, but per segment.

140
00:09:15,990 --> 00:09:19,370
And each each text message
consists of several segments,

141
00:09:19,830 --> 00:09:22,310
like from one to five mostly.

142
00:09:22,860 --> 00:09:25,420
And one segment is around 160 characters.

143
00:09:26,020 --> 00:09:29,790
On top of that, some punctuation
symbols and emojis can take more space

144
00:09:29,990 --> 00:09:32,010
and be counted as several characters.

145
00:09:32,610 --> 00:09:37,350
So while you need to communicate clearly
with the user, you also need to count

146
00:09:37,470 --> 00:09:43,780
every character you use and try not to
use the characters that take too much

147
00:09:43,830 --> 00:09:45,510
characters that take too much space.

148
00:09:46,250 --> 00:09:49,840
Then you need to combine this
with delivery problems because

149
00:09:49,850 --> 00:09:52,780
your delivery rate depends on
whether you include required

150
00:09:52,790 --> 00:09:55,430
phrases like send stop to opt out.

151
00:09:56,110 --> 00:10:01,200
It's required for like normal
delivery so the u- the user can

152
00:10:01,230 --> 00:10:07,010
send you just a message stop and
you stop sending them any new texts.

153
00:10:07,510 --> 00:10:12,380
Also, whether your message looks like
spam and whether it includes content that

154
00:10:12,380 --> 00:10:14,380
may be considered sensitive or toxic.

155
00:10:14,930 --> 00:10:19,720
For dating, which was our industry,
it's especially easy to get flagged.

156
00:10:20,440 --> 00:10:22,160
Another problem was payment links.

157
00:10:23,110 --> 00:10:28,940
We had no app, but we still need
to get payment somehow, and we sent

158
00:10:28,990 --> 00:10:34,110
the payment links by SMS and these
messages had a pretty low delivery

159
00:10:34,110 --> 00:10:36,610
rate and we were fighting with this.

160
00:10:37,190 --> 00:10:41,470
Honestly, it makes sense receiving
app payment links, receiving payment

161
00:10:41,490 --> 00:10:44,100
links by SMS can look very scammy.

162
00:10:44,520 --> 00:10:48,320
So SMS delivery was one of the pains
we had to continuously improve.

163
00:10:48,670 --> 00:10:52,020
We had to rebuild prompts,
rules and guardrails around it.

164
00:10:52,730 --> 00:10:55,749
In more traditional apps, the
paywall is already one of the

165
00:10:55,750 --> 00:11:00,040
biggest drop-off points and teams
spend a lot of time optimizing it.

166
00:11:00,040 --> 00:11:04,519
And now imagine if you get additional
drop-offs just because your

167
00:11:04,519 --> 00:11:05,789
payment message is not delivered

168
00:11:06,289 --> 00:11:07,989
The last major issue is cost.

169
00:11:08,199 --> 00:11:11,999
This is one of the main problems with
this kind of interface because every

170
00:11:11,999 --> 00:11:16,469
interaction costs you money, every
additional minute the user talks, every

171
00:11:16,469 --> 00:11:21,179
message they send, every message you
answer, all of that has a direct cost.

172
00:11:21,759 --> 00:11:24,939
And because phone-based products
have additional drop-offs poi-

173
00:11:24,959 --> 00:11:28,889
drop-off points, blocked calls,
machine answers, failed SMS delivery,

174
00:11:29,199 --> 00:11:30,909
costs can pile up pretty quickly.

175
00:11:31,429 --> 00:11:35,369
Unlike a traditional app where
many interactions are almost free

176
00:11:35,409 --> 00:11:39,269
and the user after the user is
onboarded, with the phone calls and

177
00:11:39,269 --> 00:11:42,079
SMS, every step has a marginal cost.

178
00:11:42,629 --> 00:11:46,189
Overall, I would say that this
was a great experience and a very

179
00:11:46,189 --> 00:11:47,339
interesting product to build.

180
00:11:47,779 --> 00:11:51,509
A phone call can be a powerful
interface, especially for users

181
00:11:51,509 --> 00:11:55,739
who do not want to download
another app or learn a new product.

182
00:11:56,009 --> 00:12:01,129
This can definitely be a differ-
differentiation point, but anyone

183
00:12:01,139 --> 00:12:04,659
who wants to try this should
keep in mind the downsides: trust

184
00:12:04,659 --> 00:12:09,609
issues, perception problems,
infrastructure, SMS delivery, et cetera.

185
00:12:09,609 --> 00:12:13,649
The biggest lesson for me was
that building a voice agent is not

186
00:12:13,649 --> 00:12:17,789
only about making the AI smart,
it is also about making the whole

187
00:12:17,789 --> 00:12:22,199
experience feel trustworthy,
reliable, and natural for the user

